---
import Base from "@layouts/Base.astro";

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, "");

// The 10 principles from docs/TERMINAL_NATIVE_DOCTRINE.md, condensed for the
// landing-grade format. Each principle pairs with one example app from the
// terminal-native ecosystem. The doctrine doc itself remains canonical at
// /docs/TERMINAL_NATIVE_DOCTRINE.md and is sourced under /design/.
const doctrinePrinciples = [
  {
    n: "01",
    title: "Workspace first, not page first",
    body:
      "The terminal wants to be a workspace, not a document. Stable regions: a title bar, one or more active panes, a preview, a status line.",
    exemplar: "tmux · Zellij · WezTerm · Neovim",
  },
  {
    n: "02",
    title: "Select, preview, act, confirm, stay oriented",
    body:
      "fzf made the primitive obvious. Selection is the primary navigation model — not a side effect.",
    exemplar: "fzf · Yazi · Lazygit · K9s",
  },
  {
    n: "03",
    title: "Focus, mode, and scope must always be visible",
    body:
      "Which pane is active. Which row is selected. Which mode you're in. Which command surface is listening. None of these should be hidden state.",
    exemplar: "Neovim · Helix · Kakoune",
  },
  {
    n: "04",
    title: "Discoverability is part of the interface",
    body:
      "A bottom key-hint bar, a ? overlay, a command palette. Help is not optional polish in terminal software.",
    exemplar: "Bubble Tea · WezTerm · Lazygit",
  },
  {
    n: "05",
    title: "Panes, tabs, and workspaces are native primitives",
    body:
      "Desktop GUI conventions over-index on windows, sheets, and cards. Terminal UX is panes, splits, sessions, command prompts, transient overlays.",
    exemplar: "tmux · Zellij · WezTerm",
  },
  {
    n: "06",
    title: "Full-width ownership beats floating islands",
    body:
      "Terminal screens are shallow in height and precious in width. Use the whole canvas for context, preview, and navigation.",
    exemplar: "K9s · btop · Yazi",
  },
  {
    n: "07",
    title: "Scrolling is usually pane-local, not page-level",
    body:
      "A list scrolls. A log pane scrolls. A preview scrolls. The shell stays put.",
    exemplar: "Bubble Tea viewport · Glow · Yazi previews",
  },
  {
    n: "08",
    title: "Async state belongs in the UI",
    body:
      "Loading, indeterminate progress, refresh timestamps, connected/disconnected, empty states, transient notifications. Terminal apps live in async work.",
    exemplar: "K9s · btop · LSP surfaces",
  },
  {
    n: "09",
    title: "Defaults should be restrained",
    body:
      "Little or no default fill. Borders only where they clarify structure. Accent colors for focus or one primary action. The terminal background is the canvas.",
    exemplar: "Glow · Lazygit · Helix",
  },
  {
    n: "10",
    title: "Domain-native navigation beats generic navigation",
    body:
      "The best TUIs are opinionated about how their domain is explored. Lazygit navigates branches and hunks; K9s navigates clusters and namespaces.",
    exemplar: "Lazygit · K9s · editors",
  },
];

const deviations = [
  {
    title: "Tree-forward collection presentation",
    body:
      "Hierarchical lists and outlines are more central in TUI software than they are in typical SwiftUI apps. TerminalUI treats tree-style presentation as first-class while staying close to OutlineGroup's vocabulary.",
  },
  {
    title: "Repo-owned @Bindable",
    body:
      "Ships its own bindable wrapper to keep observable editing on the same invalidation path as @State and the rest of the runtime.",
  },
  {
    title: "Terminal-native reinterpretation of defaults",
    body:
      "Automatic chrome, app-shell composition, and navigation-oriented surfaces may diverge from desktop SwiftUI precedent when modern terminal UX has a clearly better answer.",
  },
];

const deferred = [
  "NavigationStack",
  "popover presentation beyond sheet",
  "media beyond PNG / baseline JPEG / static GIF",
  "a full accessibility-tree story",
  "pixel-precise layout or a second non-terminal presentation model",
];
---

<Base
  title="Principles"
  description="Vision, philosophy, and the terminal-native doctrine that shapes TerminalUI's API decisions."
  pageKey="principles"
>
  <article class="prose article-body" style="margin-top: var(--space-2xl);">
    <p class="eyebrow">00 / Vision</p>
    <h1>Faithful to SwiftUI, native to the terminal.</h1>

    <p>
      TerminalUI is a Swift package for building terminal user interfaces with
      an authoring model, layout model, and runtime contract that are
      <em>deliberately</em> shaped after SwiftUI.
    </p>

    <p>
      The project implements the SwiftUI subset needed to build strong
      terminal applications without shortcuts in the layout algorithm, state
      model, or render pipeline. The goal is not to mimic SwiftUI cosmetically
      — the goal is to preserve the parts of SwiftUI that make large UI
      codebases predictable.
    </p>

    <h2 id="the-rule">The deviation rule</h2>

    <p>
      Deviations from SwiftUI are permitted only when all of the following are
      true:
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li>The deviation is well-considered and explicitly justified.</li>
      <li>
        The deviation solves a real terminal problem, not a copy of another
        TUI framework's habit.
      </li>
      <li>
        The deviation is documented and reflected in the public API
        inventory.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p>
      When SwiftUI precedent and terminal-native practice disagree,
      TerminalUI keeps the SwiftUI-shaped authoring story <strong>only</strong>
      if it still produces a good terminal experience. If a direct translation
      would create page-like, mouse-centric, overdecorated, or otherwise
      non-native terminal behavior, the framework reinterprets toward the
      terminal-native default.
    </p>

    <h2 id="confirmed-deviations">Confirmed deviations today</h2>

    {
      deviations.map((d) => (
        <div style="margin: var(--space-lg) 0;">
          <h3 style="margin: 0;">{d.title}</h3>
          <p style="margin: var(--space-sm) 0 0; color: var(--text-secondary);">
            {d.body}
          </p>
        </div>
      ))
    }
  </article>

  <section class="info-block" style="border-top: 1px solid var(--border);" id="doctrine">
    <div class="info-copy">
      <p class="section-label">01 / Doctrine</p>
      <h2>The 10 principles of terminal-native UX.</h2>
      <p>
        Across multiplexers, editors, operational tools, and TUI frameworks,
        the best terminal software converges on a small set of principles.
        These are evidence, not preference — sourced from the
        <a href={`${base}/research/terminal-native-ui`}>UI</a>
        and
        <a href={`${base}/research/terminal-native-ux`}>UX</a>
        research surveys.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="card-grid card-grid--three" style="grid-template-columns: 1fr;">
      {
        doctrinePrinciples.map((p) => (
          <article class="card" data-index={p.n} style="grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: var(--space-sm);">
            <h3>{p.title}</h3>
            <p>{p.body}</p>
            <span class="card-tag">{p.exemplar}</span>
          </article>
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="info-block" id="deferred">
    <div class="info-copy">
      <p class="section-label">02 / What we won't add</p>
      <h2>Restraint is a feature.</h2>
      <p>
        Some SwiftUI concepts likely belong in TerminalUI eventually. They
        will land only when the terminal-specific interaction model is clear
        and the API still reads like the same product.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="info-panel">
      <div class="info-panel-header">
        <span class="info-panel-header-file">Deferred</span>
        <span>By design</span>
      </div>
      <ul style="margin: 0; padding: var(--space-xl) var(--space-xl) var(--space-xl) calc(var(--space-xl) + var(--space-md)); list-style: none;">
        {
          deferred.map((d) => (
            <li style="margin: var(--space-sm) 0; font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 0.875rem; color: var(--text-secondary);">
              <span style="color: var(--accent); margin-right: var(--space-sm);">×</span>
              {d}
            </li>
          ))
        }
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="info-block" id="success">
    <div class="info-copy">
      <p class="section-label">03 / Success criterion</p>
      <h2>How we know it worked.</h2>
      <p>
        We consider the terminal-native reinterpretation successful when a
        new app built with TerminalUI looks and behaves like it belongs in
        the same family as the best modern terminal software.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="info-panel" style="display: grid; place-items: center; padding: var(--space-4xl) var(--space-xl); text-align: center;">
      <p style="margin: 0; font-family: var(--font-body); font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 3vw, 2.25rem); font-weight: 400; line-height: 1.2; letter-spacing: -0.02em; color: var(--text-display); max-width: 30ch;">
        It feels at home next to tmux, Zellij, WezTerm, Neovim, Yazi, and Lazygit.
      </p>
      <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2xl); font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 11px; letter-spacing: var(--label-tracking); text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--text-disabled);">
        Self-discoverable from the keyboard. Restrained chrome. Full canvas.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="info-block" style="border-bottom: 0;">
    <div class="info-copy">
      <p class="section-label">04 / What's next</p>
      <h2>Read the source.</h2>
      <p>
        These principles compile into specific design decisions. The links
        below are the unedited source documents — each is canonical in the
        repo and rendered here as part of the build.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="card-grid">
      <a class="card" href={`${base}/design/architecture`}>
        <h3>Architecture</h3>
        <p>Target boundaries and the seven-phase frame pipeline.</p>
        <span class="card-tag">→ Open</span>
      </a>
      <a class="card" href={`${base}/design/runtime`}>
        <h3>Runtime</h3>
        <p>Lifecycle, state, observation, and incremental rendering.</p>
        <span class="card-tag">→ Open</span>
      </a>
      <a class="card" href={`${base}/design/async-rendering`}>
        <h3>Async Rendering</h3>
        <p>Frame-tail offload, ordered commit, sendable layout.</p>
        <span class="card-tag">→ Open</span>
      </a>
      <a class="card" href={`${base}/start`}>
        <h3>Get started</h3>
        <p>Install, run a hello world, and find the next thing to read.</p>
        <span class="card-tag">→ 5-minute path</span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
